   </blockquote>
   
   are iid continuous G, and 
   
   <blockquote>
   U<sub>1</sub>,...,U<sub>n</sub>
   </blockquote>
   
   are iid Unif(0,1). Sort the X's as
   
   <blockquote>
   X<sub>(1)</sub> 
                   <img src=
                   "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                   align=top>
                   
                    ... 
                        <img src=
                        "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                        align=top>
                        
                         X<sub>(n)</sub>
   </blockquote>
   
   and the U's as
   
   <blockquote>
   U<sub>(1)</sub> 
                   <img src=
                   "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                   align=top>
                   
                    ... 
                        <img src=
                        "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                        align=top>
                        
                         U<sub>(n)</sub>
   </blockquote>
   
   Show that the joint distribution of the G(X<sub>(i)</sub>)'s
   is the same as that of the U<sub>(i)</sub>'s.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise ONE2.9:</font></b> 
   
   Write down the joint density of the U<sub>(i)</sub>'s defined
   above for general n. 
   For n=2 use the density to explicitly compute the distribution of
   D<sub>2</sub>. 
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       The jt density of the U's is
       
       <blockquote>
       f(u<sub>1</sub>,...,u<sub>n</sub>) = 1/n! if 
       u<sub>1</sub> 
                     <img src=
                     "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                     align=top>
                     
                      ... 
                          <img src=
                          "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                          align=top>
                          
