       </blockquote>
       
       ]
       </i>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


<h4>One-sided KS</h4>

The KS test above is a two sided one. We can also perform one-sided KS
tests. For this we need to introduce a partial order over the set of all
distributions. 
<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Definition:</b>

Let X, Y be two random variables with distribution functions F, G,
respectively. If for all c, 

<blockquote>
P(X  &gt;  c) 
              <img src=
              "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
              align=top>
              
               P(Y  &gt; c),
</blockquote>

then we say that X is stochasticaly larger than Y, and write 

<blockquote>
F 
  <img src=
  "resources/statinf2/sgeq.png"
  align=top>
  
   G.
</blockquote>


</td></tr></table>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise ONE2.10:</font></b> 
   
   Prove/disprove/suitably modify : 
   
   <blockquote>
   F 
     <img src=
     "resources/statinf2/sgeq.png"
     align=top>
     
      G iff F(x) 
                 <img src=
                 "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                 align=top>
                 
                  G(x) for all x.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise ONE2.11:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
             <img src=
             "resources/statinf2/sgeq.png"
             align=top>
             
              is a partial order on the set of all distribution
   functions. 
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise ONE2.12:</font></b> 
   
   Is it 
         <img src=
         "resources/statinf2/sgeq.png"
         align=top>
         
          a complete order as well? Why or why not?
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
In the one sided version of the KS test we test 

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/sgt.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G
</blockquote>

or

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/slt.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G.
</blockquote>

For this we use the following test statistics:

<blockquote>
D<sub>+</sub> = sup<sub>x</sub> (F<sub>n</sub>(x)-G(x))
</blockquote>

and

<blockquote>
D<sub>-</sub> = sup<sub>x</sub> (G(x)-F<sub>n</sub>(x))
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise ONE2.13:</font></b> 
   
   We reject H<sub>0</sub> for large values of the test statistic. Can you
   say which test statistic is used for which test?
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise ONE2.14:</font></b> 
   
   Show that D<sub>+</sub>, D<sub>-</sub> 
                                          <img src=
                                          "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                          align=top>
                                          
                                           0. What is the relation
   between D, D<sub>+</sub> and D<sub>-</sub>?
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

